Ludwig Mies van der Rohe was an important pioneer of modern architecture. He designed many groundbreaking skyscrapers, in Chicago, New York, and other cities. He designed the popular Barcelona chair. He coined the phrases "less is more" and "god is in the details."

I'm not saying that to blow my own horn, but to encourage folks to look into his work. Yours was not the only "who is that?" comment. Mies van der Rohe's buildings are featured on Chicago architectural tours, which are so worth seeing. The architecture of Chicago is fascinating, and this group does a bang-up job: <a href="https://www.architecture.org" target="_blank">https://www.architecture.org</a>/ If you find yourself in Chicago, I recommend them highly.

@Nora

Nice capsule review of who Ludwig Mies van der Rohe was. He’s the sort of architect that even people who don’t study architecture should know a little about. 

His influence is everywhere. When I moved to Austin in the 1970s, one of the tallest buildings downtown was a bank, the design of which owed a lot to Mies’ Seagram Building in NYC.

