@Nicholas und allen Anderen:
As an English speaker, it always causes me to smile when I see words printed with an umlaut, which we would write with a digraph, or resolve to an "e": the libretto to Hofmannsthal/Strauss' opera *Elektra*  includes roles for Klytämnestra and Ägisth.
Also, when contemporary "display" fonts use tiny "e"s as umlauts (yes, I know, that was the origin . . .).

@Nicholas

The problem here is not necessarily the spelling, but because crosswords, including those in other languages, do not use diacritics. This has led to the use of potentially inappropriate words and occasional changes in cluing to avoid the implications. For example, the word for year in Spanish is impolite with "n" instead of  "ñ", so it has lately been clued as the Portuguese word instead, which is fine without the tilde.

So, most of us realize that what you see in the crossword is not actually how it's spelled and that it would be pronounced differently.

